<p> 
</p>
<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Sixth session 
Item 10 of the agenda 
</p>
<p><b>TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND CAPACITY-BUILDING 
</b></p>
<p><b>Burkina Faso</b>*<b>, Ghana, Mauritius, Rwanda</b>*<b>, Uganda</b>*<b>, the 
United Republic of Tanzania</b>*<b>, Zambia:  draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>6/&#8230;  Advisory services and technical assistance in Burundi 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council</i>, </p>
<p><i> Reaffirming</i> that all Member States have an obligation to promote and protect human rights 
and fundamental freedoms as stated in the Charter of the United Nations, the Universal 
Declaration of Human Rights, the International Covenants on Human Rights and other 
applicable human rights instruments, 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling </i>General Assembly resolution 60/251 of 15 March 2006, 
</p>
<p><i> Mindful of </i>Commission on Human Rights resolution 2004/82 of 21 April 2004 and all the 
relevant resolutions of the General Assembly on Burundi, 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p>*  Non-member States of the Human Rights Council. </p>

 <p></p>
<p><i> Recognizing </i>the efforts by the United Nations, the African Union, the European Union and 
the countries of the Regional Peace Initiative to help provide backing to Burundi in its efforts to 
fully re-establish peace and security in its national territory, 
</p>
<p><i> Welcoming </i>the efforts of the Burundi Government and the international community to 
encourage the FNL-Palipehutu and its leader Agathon Rwasa to return to the Joint Verification 
and Monitoring Mechanism envisaged in article 3.1 of the Global Ceasefire Agreement of 
7 September 2006 and to resume negotiations, 
</p>
<p><i> Considering </i>the expectations of the Burundi population following the elections of 2005 
that led to the establishment of democratic institutions in Burundi, 
</p>
<p><i> Mindful of</i> the willingness of the Government of Burundi to engage in dialogue with its 
political partners, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Exhorts</i> the international community to provide the Burundi Government with 
appropriate funding to enable it better to consolidate human rights, peace and security in its 
national territory; 
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Encourages</i> the Burundi Government to pursue its efforts to engage in dialogue with 
FNL-Palipehutu and its leader Agathon Rwasa; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Also</i> <i>encourages</i> the Burundi Government to continue to give priority to dialogue, 
wherever necessary; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Decides </i>to extend for one year the mandate of the independent expert to provide 
backing for the Burundi Government in its efforts to improve the human rights situation; 
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Requests </i>the High Commissioner for Human Rights to increase the allocation for 
technical assistance for Burundi through her office in Bujumbura; 
</p>
<p> 6. <i>Also requests</i> the High Commissioner to mobilize funding for, inter alia, a 
capacity-building programme for the national police and justice system in Burundi; 
</p>
<p> 7. <i>Asks</i> the independent expert to submit a progress report to the General Assembly at 
its sixty-third session and a final report to the Council at its ninth session. 
</p>
<p>----- </p>

